      {
        "id": "6cec56aaa5da17b87d543a71e3d1449bd4cbc349",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 97,
          "name": "Max Benjamin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "max.benjamin@att.com",
          "username": "mfour"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-06-26 18:17:26.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "09f027f540c4a881f8efe2e8cb17b01fd2ddec20",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2789,
          "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
          "username": "lukaszM"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-06-27 09:47:34.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> (1 comment)\n\nHi Rob, I did it this way because in the previuous implementation (reading from properties file from resource project folder) when we want to change dmaap host and port, it causes we need to rebuild docker image, what is not good. \n\nWhat about reading from external file? That file would be place for example in etc folder and host and port for dmaap will be read from there each time when they are needed. \nDo you think is this better idea?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "0352400b46fd7951b019ffa6a5e31524998aaaaa",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 97,
          "name": "Max Benjamin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "max.benjamin@att.com",
          "username": "mfour"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-06-27 13:58:25.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n\nI believe there is already a way to read properties from an external file. The other parts of SO do this already, I don't remember where it is in the code. There are properties files for api-handler, adapters, and bpmn. The dmaap properties can be copied to one of those. If this work is not time sensitive I would defer it until containerized SO is released in a week or two.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "3c8e8479853e30651ff82fa171373e51b913c7c1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3395,
          "name": "Marcin Migdal",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "marcin.migdal@nokia.com",
          "username": "mmigdal"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-06-28 13:43:50.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "a8a8de68b2d92b1bce6769514a08ebdf3709e4e7",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3395,
          "name": "Marcin Migdal",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "marcin.migdal@nokia.com",
          "username": "mmigdal"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-06-28 13:46:28.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHello,\n\nhere is already a way to read properties from an external file.\nFiles in cloud environemtn? Why not to pass then as variables for Kubernetes?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "b24bc94b2ea8781ac74d251d1049492047a4f413",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2789,
          "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
          "username": "lukaszM"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-03 12:07:20.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> (1 comment)\n\nI analised the current properties implementation. It allows for configuration in mso-docker.json file, which is placed in docker-config repo. The property files are generated from this json file. The problem is that if we want to change configiuration in json file, we have to restart application. It would be good idea to have a possiblity to change config dynamically, without the need of restart. \nIn the current code, we have WatchEvent implementation for changes property files for etc/mso/config.d. But it is not safe, because after restart these files are generated and all changes are lost. Putting dmaap host and port as enviromental variables let us have possibility for dynamic changes. Rob, what do you think?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "e850967a85f99a38f9f6bec0d63898dd30b90efd",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 63,
          "name": "Steve Smokowski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "ss835w@att.com",
          "username": "SteveSmokowski"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-03 12:21:32.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nWhy do we need dynamic configuration of a host name/port?  I am not sure what the issue is with just re installing the docker image to pick up the latest config is?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "7afbcb85c531ecfe8401d737a08ffecaf0e21e62",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2789,
          "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
          "username": "lukaszM"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-03 13:24:27.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Why do we need dynamic configuration of a host name/port?  I am not\n > sure what the issue is with just re installing the docker image to\n > pick up the latest config is?\n\nIt would be more comfortable way to pick up the latest dmaap config without restart, what if we want to change for example dmaap ip and currently we can not restart so because some tasks are performed. Anyway, for now I can do it as it is, to use mso-docker.json file. If there is a need, I will come back to this topic in the future.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
